This very representation of a life foreign to the audience imposed many restrictions on the adapter. He must perforce cut out all characters that would be incomprehensible to an ordinary Roman. He must trim the conversation, the dishesâ€š the jokes down to the level of his hearers. These remarks may serve to explain at once why the treatment of the originals is so free and why the life described is so essentially un-Roman.
